			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=95709'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=wizardbalance&message.id=2663#M2663">119</a> of 234
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 276 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Sure, if you make manaburn a 500k nuke that is instant cast, takes no mana, has no refresh, is irresistible, and has no limit in terms of number of people that can cast it, then it would be useful.  But we all know that this is not going to happen.<br><br>First of all, they have already stated that they are ont removing the 1 manaburn per minute restriction.  The reason for this is that a relatively small group of wizards could just run around destroying raid content mobs.  Back in Luclin, mobs had very high hit points, preventing even a large group of wizards from manaburning through raid mobs.  This bored people to tears, and most of the people in the high end game in Luclin complained that fights were incredibly long and boring.  In an attempt to make fights more fun, and shorter (i.e. not endurance based), SOE introduced with PoP lower hp boss mobs that had other things about them that made them challenging.  This would have been impossible without the 1 manaburn per minute restriction.<br><br>Thus, SOE will not remove that restriction, as it would trivialize a lot of raid content from PoP and some later expansions, and forever remove their ability to have low hp mobs that are challenging for other reasons.  Personally, I don't think they should remove the restriction, as I don't want to go back to raiding mobs that take an hour to kill with a 50 man raid.  That would be the result.<br><br>As far as SOE sees it, the problem with manaburn is that while our manapools have increased dramatically (I was top on my server in Luclin with about 4.5k, nowadays 11k is not uncommon at all), the cap on manaburn has not.  They want to make the cap a percentage of mob hp instead of a fixed number, which essentially makes manaburn useless again, as it would never do a very large percentage of a mob's hp, and it still wouldn't be stackable.  Considering the possible modifications that are reasonably likely for manaburn, it will remain a useless toy.  It might become somewhat less useless, but it will still be useless.  It is not going to be a 100k nuke.  There have been no proposed changes to it's mana/hp ratio, just to the cap, so that would make crit manaburns for the top wizards in EQ somewhere in the 40k range.  These would be extremely rare, with average manaburns for high end 12k mana wizards landing for somewhere in the 15-20k range.  (All of this assumes that the mobs hp are high enough for that not to take too large a percentage of the mob's health.)  I don't oppose the proposed changes to manaburn.  I think lifting the cap would be a good thing.  However, I expect that that will not increase my dps at all, in either burst or sustained situations, in 99% of cases.<br><br>Seeing as I currently do 25% of the damage of a rogue sustained over time, I see that as THE MAJOR ISSUE with the wizard class, and I'm increasingly concerned that all of this manaburn talk will cause them to divert valuable resources from the real problem, which is our sustained and burst dps.  We already understand the changes that are being made to manaburn, so let's just say "ok neat, cool toy, now let's move on to the real stuff".	
		</td></tr>
