<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/gnome.jpg" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=wizardbalance&message.id=2673#M2673">122</a> of 234
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 233 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>Gnomish Greetings!<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Ammelen wrote:<BR>Sure, if you make manaburn a 500k nuke that is instant cast, takes no mana, has no refresh, is irresistible, and has no limit in terms of number of people that can cast it, then it would be useful. But we all know that this is not going to happen.<BR><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>You don't need it to be an instant death touch for it to be useful.&nbsp; Yes, we all know that instant death touch is not going to be in the wizard line up.&nbsp;&nbsp;If we are a&nbsp;little more imaginative in what could be done, then perhaps we can work on a solution.&nbsp; I don't think SOE has the right solution yet, but they are not being forthcoming in the exact details.&nbsp;&nbsp;<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Ammelen wrote:<BR>First of all, they have already stated that they are ont removing the 1 manaburn per minute restriction. The reason for this is that a relatively small group of wizards could just run around destroying raid content mobs. Back in Luclin, mobs had very high hit points, preventing even a large group of wizards from manaburning through raid mobs. This bored people to tears, and most of the people in the high end game in Luclin complained that fights were incredibly long and boring. In an attempt to make fights more fun, and shorter (i.e. not endurance based), SOE introduced with PoP lower hp boss mobs that had other things about them that made them challenging. This would have been impossible without the 1 manaburn per minute restriction.<BR><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>First of all, no they haven't said they aren't removing the one minute timer as far as I can see.&nbsp; Brenlo's post alluded to the possibility, but the description is vague enough that it could be interpretted a number of ways.&nbsp;</P>
<P>After they nerfed Manaburn and Trods, they "re-tuned" Luclin boss encounters.&nbsp; They were still long fights, most of PoP was similar except it had trash mobs or other scripted encounters and still the vast majority of encounters had too many hit points to trivialize with Manaburn.&nbsp; PoP was a good expansion, but it was not a valid reason to nerf Manaburn as badly as they did.&nbsp; The only time it made any sense to use Manaburn is when it was faster than conventional nukes.&nbsp; So, somewhere along the lines of about 2 minutes, you were better off not using Manaburn.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because of the&nbsp;scripted encounters that required the use of your mana, so even those with lower hitpoints Manaburn would not have been useful.</P>
<P>If this 1 minute timer was so crucial to balance, then why was it applied to only wizard's fast damage ability?&nbsp; It's not crucial for balance.&nbsp; It seems it was more a punitive measure to discourage the farming of old content because people were unhappy at those who abused it and denied others epic progression.&nbsp; A cap may have been necessary, but not the re-burn timer.&nbsp; They could have capped the mana used as well, to keep this from being an ability of diminished return.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Ammelen wrote:<BR>As far as SOE sees it, the problem with manaburn is that while our manapools have increased dramatically (I was top on my server in Luclin with about 4.5k, nowadays 11k is not uncommon at all), the cap on manaburn has not. They want to make the cap a percentage of mob hp instead of a fixed number, which essentially makes manaburn useless again, as it would never do a very large percentage of a mob's hp, and it still wouldn't be stackable. Considering the possible modifications that are reasonably likely for manaburn, it will remain a useless toy. It might become somewhat less useless, but it will still be useless. It is not going to be a 100k nuke. There have been no proposed changes to it's mana/hp ratio, just to the cap, so that would make crit manaburns for the top wizards in EQ somewhere in the 40k range. These would be extremely rare, with average manaburns for high end 12k mana wizards landing for somewhere in the 15-20k range. (All of this assumes that the mobs hp are high enough for that not to take too large a percentage of the mob's health.) I don't oppose the proposed changes to manaburn. I think lifting the cap would be a good thing. However, I expect that that will not increase my dps at all, in either burst or sustained situations, in 99% of cases.<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Have developers spoken with you personally?&nbsp; How do you know how SOE sees it, or if they even see it correctly?&nbsp; I don't think you have considered all of the possibilities for a fix, for there have been many.&nbsp; If we, the wizards who would like to see Manaburn fixed, don't like the change, then why should your view matter at all if you are&nbsp;so sure&nbsp;it will always be a useless toy?&nbsp; I am convinced there are a percentage of those who just want SOE to do something (even meaningless) just so you can call it done regardless of how those who want to use the ability feel.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>
Ammelen wrote:<BR>Seeing as I currently do 25% of the damage of a rogue sustained over time, I see that as THE MAJOR ISSUE with the wizard class, and I'm increasingly concerned that all of this manaburn talk will cause them to divert valuable resources from the real problem, which is our sustained and burst dps.
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I assume you read Graffe's and know about Claw of Vox, perhaps you have even read what some are saying about over inflated sustained rogue dps numbers.&nbsp; Either way, SOE has commited to making more changes in line with Claw of Vox AND fixing the rain resist issue.&nbsp; That&nbsp;will&nbsp;do a lot for Wizard sustained dps numbers.</P>
<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<HR>

<P>Ammelen wrote:<BR>We already understand the changes that are being made to manaburn, so let's just say "ok neat, cool toy, now let's move on to the real stuff".</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Not only is it unclear what the changes are going to entail, <STRONG>it is quite likely to make the ability less useful </STRONG>to those who might use it if it is implemented as some wizards <STRONG>have guessed </STRONG>it is designed.&nbsp; So lets just let those who wanted to see the change have a wee bit of input, and not those who have practically no stake it please.&nbsp; For a lot of wizards Manaburn is part of the real stuff, which is why it was so popular for the top 10 list originally.</P>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<DIV><STRONG><FONT size=2>Happy Birthday Wizard top 10 List!</FONT></STRONG><span></span><br><DIV><STRONG><FONT size=3><A href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=26846" target=_blank>Manaburn Manifesto on Graffe</A></FONT></STRONG><span></span>
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
